5.	Explain the client-server architecture of the web with a neat diagram.
The client–server architecture is a model where the client (usually a web browser) sends a request to the server, and the server processes the request and sends back the required response. The client is responsible for the user interface, while the server stores data, runs applications, and delivers web content. Communication between them happens through protocols like HTTP/HTTPS.
•	Client (Web Browser): Requests web pages or services.
•	Server (Web Server): Processes requests, fetches data, and sends responses.
•	Interaction: The client initiates communication, and the server responds accordingly.
