7. ”The Internet is a network of networks.” Elaborate on this statement explaining how packet switching works.
The Internet is called a “network of networks” because it links together millions of smaller networks from homes, schools, businesses, and governments into one global system. This massive connection works through a process called packet switching, where any data you send such as a message, video, or file is broken into small units called packets. Each packet carries part of the data along with addressing information and travels independently across different routes in the network. When they reach the destination, the packets are reassembled in the correct order to form the original message. This method makes communication faster, more reliable, and efficient, even if some routes are busy or fail.

