8. A startup company wants to host a website that displays the same information to all     visitors and requires very low maintenance costs. However, they are being advised to use a dynamic website. As a consultant, would you agree? Justify your answer.
If a startup wants to host a website that shows the same information to all visitors and keep costs low, then a static website is the right choice. Static sites are simple to design, cheaper to host, and require very little maintenance because the content does not change often. On the other hand, a dynamic website is more complex, needs server side processing, and involves higher costs for hosting and regular updates. Since the company’s goal is low maintenance and fixed information, I would not recommend a dynamic site; a static website will serve their purpose more efficiently and economically.

9. A user types www.google.com into their browser, but the browser displays a ”Server Not Found” error, even though the internet connection is active. However, accessing the site via 142.250.190.46 works. Diagnose the problem and explain the underlying technology that failed.
    If typing www.google.com shows “Server Not Found” but the site opens when you use the IP address 142.250.190.46, the problem is with the Domain Name System (DNS). The Internet actually works with numbers (IP addresses), but since those are hard to remember, DNS acts like a phonebook that translates easy names (like google.com) into those numbers. In this case, the Internet connection is fine, and Google’s server is reachable, but the DNS service failed to translate the domain name into its IP address. That’s why the browser couldn’t find the server using the name, but it worked when you typed the IP directly. So the underlying technology that failed here is DNS resolution.
10. A multinational corporation wants to share sensitive inventory data with specific suppliers but does not want this information available to the general public. Explain which network type (Intranet, Extranet, or Internet) they should implement and why.
   For this situation, the company should use an Extranet. An Intranet is only for internal employees, and the Internet is open to everyone, which would expose sensitive data. An Extranet, however, is a private network that extends part of the company’s internal system to trusted external partners, like specific suppliers. This way, the corporation can securely share inventory information with those suppliers while keeping it hidden from the general public. It gives controlled access, protects sensitive data, and ensures that only authorized users outside the company can see what they need.







